column4: Description

Start in a plank position with hands under shoulders, lower your body until elbows reach about 90 degrees while keeping the body straight, then push back uphttps://www.health.harvard.edu/blog/rise-push-ups-classic-exercise-can-motivate-get-stronger-2019021810165#:~:text=To%20maximize%20what%20push,you%20should%20perform%20them%20correctly.
Place your hands on an elevated surface (like a bench), keep a straight line from head to heels, lower chest to the surface and push back up.
Place your feet on an elevated surface, hands on the floor under shoulders; lower chest toward the floor and press back up while keeping body straight.
From a plank, position your hands together under your chest with thumbs and index fingers forming a diamond; lower your body and push back up.
Perform a push-up with hands placed wider than shoulder-width apart to emphasise the chest; keep body straight and avoid flaring elbows excessively.
Sit with dumbbells on your thighs, then lie back on a bench and position weights at the sides of your chest; press the dumbbells up until arms are extended and lower back to chest level.
Lie back on an incline bench with dumbbells at chest level; press them up until arms are extended over your shoulders and slowly lower.
Lie back on a decline bench holding dumbbells; press them upward and inward, then lower toward the sides of your chest in a controlled motion.
Lie on a bench with feet flat, grip the bar slightly wider than shoulder width, lower it to your chest while controlling the descent, then press it back up to armâ€™s length.
Lie on a bench holding dumbbells above your chest with arms slightly bent; open arms wide in an arc until you feel a stretch in the chest, then bring weights back together.
Stand between two cable stacks with arms extended and slight elbow bend; bring the handles together in front of your chest using a hugging motion, then return.
Sit on a chest press machine with handles at chest height; press handles forward until arms are extended, then return slowly.
Hang from a bar with an overhand grip slightly wider than shoulder width; pull yourself up until your chin clears the bar, then lower with control.
Hang from a bar with a supinated (underhand) grip about shoulder width; pull your chest toward the bar and lower back down slowly.

Sit at a cable lat pulldown station holding the bar with a wide overhand grip; draw the bar down to your upper chest while squeezing your back, then return slowlyhttps://www.jefit.com/exercises/86/cable-lat-pulldown-wide-grip#:~:text=The%20wide,back%20to%20the%20starting%20position.
Stand with knees slightly bent, hinge at the hips keeping a flat back, hold the barbell with an overhand grip, pull it toward your lower ribs, then lower.
Place one knee and hand on a bench, hold a dumbbell in the other hand, keep back flat, row the weight toward your hip, then lower.
Straddle a landmine or T-bar attachment, bend at the hips with a neutral spine, grasp handles, pull the bar to your chest and lower.
Sit at a cable row machine with knees slightly bent; grab the handle, pull it toward your torso while keeping your back straight, then extend arms.
Position a bar at hip height, hang underneath with a straight body, pull chest to the bar and lower yourself back to straight arms.
Lie face down with arms and legs extended; simultaneously lift arms, chest and legs off the floor, hold briefly, then lower.
Lie face down on a hyperextension bench with feet secured; bend at the waist to lower torso, then contract your back to raise back to neutral.
Bend at the hips with a flat back, hold dumbbells under shoulders; raise arms out to sides until they reach shoulder height, then lower.
Place a barbell on your upper back, stand with feet shoulder-width, hinge at hips with a slight knee bend while keeping back flat, then return upright.
With feet hip-width apart, hinge at hips and knees to grasp the bar on the floor; lift by driving through the heels and extending hips and knees, then lower with control.
Hold the bar at hip level, hinge at the hips with slight knee bend lowering the bar along the thighs until you feel a stretch in hamstrings, then return to standing.
Start with bar at hip height; with knees nearly straight, hinge forward and lower the bar towards the feet while keeping back flat, then rise back up.

Stand or sit with dumbbells at shoulder level; press the weights overhead, pause briefly, then lower them back to shouldershttps://www.verywellfit.com/how-to-do-the-dumbbell-overhead-press-3498298#:~:text=Stand%20upright%20and%20keep%20the,inside%20and%20knuckles%20face%20up.
Start seated with dumbbells held in front of shoulders, palms facing body; as you press up, rotate palms to face forward; reverse motion when lowering.
Stand with barbell at shoulder level using overhand grip; press it overhead until arms are extended, then lower to shoulders.
Stand with arms at sides holding dumbbells; raise arms out to the sides until they reach shoulder height, maintaining a slight bend in elbows, then lower.
Holding dumbbells at your thighs, raise arms straight in front to shoulder height, keeping elbows slightly bent, then lower.
Lean forward with back flat, lift dumbbells out to the side until elbows are at shoulder height, then return.
Hold a barbell or dumbbells in front of thighs; pull them up along your body toward your chest with elbows leading high, then lower.
Stand holding weights at your sides; lift your shoulders toward your ears, pause, then lower back down.
Attach a rope to a high pulley; pull the rope toward your face keeping elbows high and squeezing rear delts, then extend arms.
Dip at the knees slightly and explosively press the weight overhead, using leg drive; lower back under control.
Stand with dumbbells at your sides, palms facing forward; curl the weights up toward your shoulders while keeping elbows stationary, then lower.
Hold dumbbells with palms facing in (neutral grip); curl weights up while keeping elbows close to your body, then lower.
Sit and brace your upper arm against your inner thigh; curl a dumbbell up toward your shoulder, then lower.
Stand holding a barbell with an underhand grip; curl it toward your shoulders while keeping elbows still, then lower.
Sit at a preacher bench with arms over the pad; curl the weight up toward your shoulders, then lower under control.
Attach a straight bar to a low cable; curl the bar toward your shoulders while keeping elbows by your sides, then lower.
Grip parallel bars with arms straight and body upright; lower yourself by bending elbows until they reach roughly 90 degrees, then press back up.
Place hands on a bench behind you, extend legs forward; lower your hips by bending elbows, then push back up.
Attach a rope or bar to a high cable; keeping elbows at your sides, extend your arms to push the attachment down, then return.
Hold a dumbbell with both hands overhead, lower it behind your head by bending elbows, then extend arms to raise it back up.
Lie on a bench with arms extended holding a bar above your chest; bend elbows to lower the bar toward your forehead, then extend to the starting position.
Hinge at the hips with a flat back, hold dumbbell with elbow bent; extend your arm behind you until straight, then return.

Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, engage core and send hips back as if sitting in a chair; lower until thighs are parallel or lower, then push through heels to standfile:///home/oai/redirect.html#:~:text=1.%20Stand%20with%20feet%20shoulder,return%20to%20a%20standing%20position.

Rest the barbell on your upper back, stand with feet slightly wider than shoulder width; squat by bending knees and hips while keeping your torso upright, then drive through heels to standhttps://www.verywellfit.com/safe-squat-technique-3119136#:~:text=1,three%20sets%20of%20six%20to.
Hold the barbell on the front of your shoulders (front rack), keep elbows high; squat down with an upright torso and stand back up.
Hold a dumbbell or kettlebell close to your chest with both hands; squat down by sitting back and keeping chest up, then press through heels to stand.
Stand with feet wider than shoulder-width and toes turned out; squat down keeping knees aligned with toes and back straight, then return to standing.
Stand with one foot forward and one foot back; lower your body by bending both knees until the back knee nearly touches the floor, then press back up.
Place your rear foot on a bench behind you; lower your body by bending the front knee until the back knee nearly touches the floor, then rise back up.

From standing, step forward into a split stance and lower until your back knee is close to the floor and front thigh is parallel, then push through the front heel to returnhttps://www.verywellfit.com/how-to-lunge-variations-modifications-and-mistakes-1231320#:~:text=Stand%20in%20a%20split%20stance,are%20resting%20on%20your%20hips.
Step backward with one foot, lower your body until both knees are bent at 90 degrees, then return to standing.
Take a wide step to the side and bend the stepping knee while pushing your hips back; keep the opposite leg straight, then return to standing.
Perform consecutive forward lunges by stepping forward with each stride, lowering and rising before stepping into the next lunge.
Stand in front of a bench or box; place one foot on the platform and press through that leg to step up, then step down and repeat on the other side.
Stand on one leg, extend the other leg forward; squat down on the working leg keeping the extended leg off the ground, then stand back up.
Sit on a leg press machine with feet on the platform; release the safety, lower the sled until knees are about 90 degrees, then press through your feet to return.
Sit on a leg extension machine with shins under the pad; extend your knees to lift the weight, then lower slowly.
Lie face down on a leg curl machine with the pad behind your ankles; curl your legs toward your glutes, then lower the weight back down.
Stand with the balls of your feet on an elevated surface; rise up onto your toes to lift your heels, pause, then lower back down.
Sit with a weight pad over your knees and the balls of your feet on a platform; raise your heels as high as possible, then lower.
Lie on your back with knees bent and feet on the floor; lift your hips by squeezing glutes until body forms a straight line from shoulders to knees, then lower.
Place your upper back on a bench with knees bent and feet planted; rest a barbell across your hips, thrust hips upward by squeezing glutes, then lower.
Lie on your side with legs straight; lift the top leg upward while keeping it straight, pause, then lower.
Lie on your side or sit on an adduction machine; bring your lower leg upward or squeeze pads together to engage the inner thighs.
Stand in front of a box; jump explosively onto the box landing softly with both feet, then step back down.
Perform a squat and then explosively jump upward, landing softly and transitioning into the next rep.
Start in a lunge position, jump up and switch legs midair to land in a lunge with the opposite leg forward.
Stand with feet shoulder-width apart holding a kettlebell; hinge at the hips to swing the kettlebell back between your legs and then drive hips forward to swing it to chest height.
Hold a kettlebell by the horns at chest level; squat down while keeping the chest up and elbows inside the knees, then drive back up.
Lie on your back with knees bent and hands behind head; lift your head and shoulders toward your knees by engaging your abs, then lower down.
Lie on your back with knees bent and feet anchored; curl your torso up toward your thighs and then return to the starting position.
Lie on your back with knees bent at 90 degrees; use your lower abs to curl your hips off the floor toward your chest, then lower slowly.
Lie on your back and lift shoulders and knees; alternate bringing opposite elbow to knee while extending the other leg in a pedaling motion.
Sit with knees bent and lean back slightly; hold hands or weight in front of chest and rotate torso from side to side.
Lie on your back with legs straight; lift your legs up until they are perpendicular to the floor, then lower them without touching the ground.
Lie on your back with legs extended slightly off the floor; kick your legs up and down alternately in a quick, controlled motion.
Start in a plank position; alternate driving knees toward your chest in a running motion while maintaining plank alignment.
Hold your body in a straight line from head to heels, supported on forearms and toes; engage your core and avoid dropping hips.
Lie on your side and prop yourself up on one forearm with legs stacked; lift hips to create a straight line and hold, then switch sides.
On hands and knees, extend opposite arm and leg while keeping hips and shoulders squared; return and repeat on the other side.
Lie on your back with arms extended above shoulders and knees bent; lower one arm and the opposite leg toward the floor while keeping back flat, then return and alternate.
Lie flat with arms extended overhead; simultaneously lift your legs and upper body, reaching hands toward your toes to form a V shape, then lower.
Lie on your back with arms overhead and legs extended; lift arms and legs slightly off the ground while pressing your lower back into the floor and hold.
Hang from a bar with legs straight; raise legs up until they form a 90-degree angle with your torso, then lower.
Lie on your back with arms out for support and legs up; rotate legs side to side like windshield wipers while keeping shoulders on the ground.
Kneel holding an ab wheel; roll it forward while keeping your back flat and core engaged, then pull back to the starting position.
Attach a handle to a high cable; stand sideways and pull the handle diagonally across your body toward the opposite knee using your core, then return and repeat both sides.
Lie flat with arms overhead and legs straight; bring arms and legs together by lifting both simultaneously, reaching hands toward your shins, then lower.
From standing, squat down, kick your feet back into a plank, do a push-up, jump feet forward to squat and explosively jump up.
Stand with arms at sides; jump feet out wide while raising arms overhead, then jump back to the starting position.
Swing a kettlebell between your legs, then drive through hips to propel it overhead in one motion finishing with the kettlebell overhead and arm straight.
Lift the barbell from the floor to shoulder level (clean) using hip drive, then press it overhead; lower back to shoulders and then to the floor.
Hold weights at shoulder level, perform a full squat and then immediately drive up while pressing the weights overhead in one fluid movement.
Lie on your back holding a kettlebell overhead with one arm; stand up through a series of lunge and bridge positions while keeping the kettlebell overhead, then reverse back down.
Lift a medicine ball overhead and explosively slam it onto the ground, catching it on the rebound.
Hold the ends of battle ropes; raise both arms overhead and slam the ropes down forcefully, repeating rapidly.
Pick up heavy weights in each hand and walk a set distance while keeping your torso tall and core engaged.
